Moments in Canadian LGBT+ History

1995

Jim Egan, one of Canada’s first gay activists, brought a case to the supreme court with his partner, Jack Nesbitt. After turning 65 in Canada, citizens are eligible from old-age security and income supplements as well as a spousal allowance in they have a combined income under a certain threshold. Egan applied on Nesbitt’s behalf for a spousal allowance and was denied on the basis of his gender. Taking this all the way to the Supreme Court, The appeal was lost, however, Egan v. Canada ruled that “sexual orientation” is in the Charter as a ground of discrimination, thus providing protection from discrimination based on sexual orientation. This case marks the first big win for LGBT+ rights in Canada.

1981

The Toronto bathhouse raids, also known as ‘Operation Soap’ took place on February 5, 1981. 200 police officers raided four bathhouses in downtown Toronto (The Barracks, The Club, Richmond Street Health Emporium, and Roman II Health and Recreation Spa) for alleged sex work and ‘indecent acts’. Bathhouse patrons were subjected to police brutality, hate speech and mass destruction of property. To date, Operation Soap remains Toronto’s largest mass arrest, with 286 men charged with being found in a bawdy house (a brothel). On February 6, 1981 over 3000 protesters took to the streets to protest police violence against the gay community. This protest quickly turned into a riot against the police force and catalized Canada’s gay rights movement. On the 35 anniversary of the raids, the Toronto police chief officially apologized for Operation Soap.

1974

On January 5, 1974 four women were dragged out of the Brunswick Tavern in Toronto by police for singing an original song entitled “I Enjoy Being a Dyke”. The women in question were Adrienne Potts, Pat Murphy, Sue Wells and Heather Beyer and identified as lesbians. The Brunswick Four as they were called were subject to verbal harassed and taken to the police station and denied the right to an attorney. Adrienne Potts, Pat Murphy, Sue Wells and Heather Beyer returned to the bar later that evening to collect statements from witnesses and were again ousted from the establishment by police and charged with causing a disturbance.

1960's

In the early 1960's, a device was designed to detect homosexuality by a psychology professor, Frank Robert Wake. The 'Fruit Machine' measured the size of ones pupils when shown pornography. If the subjects pupils were enlarged after consuming gay pornography, they were identified as a homosexual. The Canadian government funded this project and it was used to discriminate against LGBT Canadians in civil service and the military.
